{{#format}}
<p>
<strong>You must enter something for each cell of the matrix.</strong> Please don't leave any cells blank.
Each component of your answer must be a symbolic expression. For best results, try to use rational numbers; for example, <code>1/2</code> instead of <code>0.5</code>.
<hr>
<h5><small class='text-uppercase'>Allowable Operators</small></h5>
<pre>{{operators}}</pre>
<p>All operations must be explicit - examples of valid expressions are <code>cos(1)</code> and <code>2*(3)</code>. Examples of invalid expressions are <code>cos 1</code> and <code>2(3)</code>. Note that either <code>^</code> or <code>**</code> can be used for exponentiation. For example, <code>2**3</code> is the same as: <code>2*2*2</code></p>
<hr>
<h5><small class='text-uppercase'>Allowable Constants</small></h5>
<pre>{{constants}}</pre>
<hr>
<h5><small class='text-uppercase'>Complex Numbers</small></h5>
{{^allow_complex}}<strong>For this input field, complex numbers are not allowed.</strong>{{/allow_complex}}
{{#allow_complex}}
<p>Either <code>i</code> or <code>j</code> can be used to denote the imaginary unit. Examples of valid complex numbers are <code>1 + 2 * i</code> and <code>-3 * j</code>.</p>
{{/allow_complex}}
<hr>
<h5><small class='text-uppercase'>Allowable Variables</small></h5>
{{^variables}}<strong>For this input field, variables are not allowed.</strong>{{/variables}}
{{#variables}}
<pre>{{variables}}</pre>
<p><strong>Be sure to explicitly multiply variables by coefficients.</strong> For example, if <code>x</code> is an acceptable variable, you could write <code>2*x</code>, but <em>not</em> "2x". If x and y are acceptable variables, you could input the expression <code>2*x*x*x&nbsp;+&nbsp;5*y</code> as: <code>2*x**3&nbsp;+&nbsp;5*y</code></p>
{{/variables}}
</p>
{{/format}}

